<h2>GBP Engagement Statistics</h2>
<p><strong>9. The average verified GBP receives approximately 1,800 impressions per month.</strong>
(Source: Birdeye, 2025)
Impressions measure how often your profile appears in search results and Maps.</p>
<p><strong>10. 84% of GBP impressions come from discovery searches, not direct brand searches.</strong>
(Source: Birdeye, 2025)
Most people who see your profile are searching for a service or product, not your business name. This makes <a href="/blog/local-keyword-research/">local keyword optimization</a> critical.</p>
<p><strong>11. The average GBP drives about 200 clicks per month.</strong>
(Source: Birdeye, 2025)
200 clicks from local searchers with high purchase intent represent significant business value.</p>
<p><strong>12. 48% of GBP actions are website visits. 21% are calls. 9% are direction requests.</strong>
(Source: Birdeye, 2025)
Nearly half of all GBP engagement drives traffic directly to your website.</p>
<p><strong>13. The average GBP generates 105 monthly website visits.</strong>
(Source: Birdeye, 2025)
Free, high-intent traffic from local searchers every single month.</p>
<p><strong>14. The average GBP generates 50 calls per month and 595 calls per year.</strong>
(Source: Birdeye, 2025)
For service businesses, those 50 monthly calls represent real revenue opportunities.</p>
<p><strong>15. 90% of weekday business calls originate from Google Business Profile.</strong>
(Source: Birdeye, 2025)
GBP is the primary source of phone leads for most local businesses.</p>
<p><strong>16. 24% of GBP businesses receive 50 or more calls per month from their profile.</strong>
(Source: Birdeye, 2025)
The top-performing quarter of businesses generate significant call volume from GBP alone.</p>
<p><strong>17. 40% of businesses exceed 1,000 monthly GBP impressions.</strong>
(Source: Birdeye, 2025)
Businesses with optimized profiles and regular activity see disproportionately higher visibility.</p>
<p><strong>18. Hospitality businesses average 92,626 monthly search views.</strong>
(Source: Birdeye, 2025)
Industry matters enormously. Hospitality dominates GBP impressions.</p>
<h2>GBP Review Statistics</h2>
<p><strong>19. 97% of consumers read reviews for local businesses before making a decision.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/research/local-consumer-review-survey/">BrightLocal</a>, 2025)
Reviews are no longer optional. Nearly every potential customer reads them.</p>
<p><strong>20. The average local business has 39 Google reviews.</strong>
(Source: BrightLocal, 2025)
Top-ranking businesses average 47 reviews. More reviews correlate with higher rankings.</p>
<p><strong>21. 74% of local businesses have at least 1 Google review.</strong>
(Source: BrightLocal, 2025)
26% of local businesses have zero reviews. Those businesses are invisible to review-conscious consumers.</p>
<p><strong>22. The average star rating for local businesses is 4.42 stars.</strong>
(Source: BrightLocal, 2025)
61% of businesses rate between 4 and 5 stars. Only 5% rate below 3 stars.</p>
<p><strong>23. Businesses earn an average of 66 new reviews per location annually.</strong>
(Source: Birdeye, 2025)
Hospitality businesses earn 281 per year. Finance businesses earn 23. Industry variation is significant.</p>
<p><strong>24. 63% of consumers would lose trust in a business with mostly negative reviews.</strong>
(Source: BrightLocal, 2025)
<a href="/blog/get-more-google-reviews-local-business/">Review management</a> directly impacts consumer trust and purchasing decisions.</p>
<p><strong>25. 73% of consumers only trust reviews written in the last month.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://wiserreview.com/blog/google-review-statistics/">WiserReview</a>, 2026)
Review recency matters as much as review volume. Fresh reviews signal an active, current business.</p>
<p><strong>26. Businesses that respond to reviews see 12% more engagement than those that do not.</strong>
(Source: Google, 2025)
Response rate is a ranking signal and a trust signal. Responding to every review pays dividends.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Google Business Profile review statistics for 2026" src="/images/blog/gbp-review-stats.webp" /></p>
<h2>GBP Photo and Content Statistics</h2>
<p><strong>27. Google Business Profiles with photos receive 42% more direction requests.</strong>
(Source: Google, 2025)
Photos are not decorative. They drive measurable action.</p>
<p><strong>28. Profiles with photos receive 35% more website clicks.</strong>
(Source: Google, 2025)
<a href="/blog/gbp-photos-guide/">GBP photos</a> directly increase traffic to your website.</p>
<p><strong>29. Businesses with 100+ photos see 520% more calls, 2,700% more direction requests, and 1,065% more website clicks.</strong>
(Source: BrightLocal, 2025)
The difference between 10 photos and 100 photos is not linear. It is exponential.</p>
<p><strong>30. The average GBP has 26 photos.</strong>
(Source: Birdeye, 2025)
Home services businesses average 70 photos. Finance businesses average 6.</p>
<p><strong>31. Top-ranking Google Business Profiles average 250 images.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://bloggingwizard.com/google-business-profile-statistics/">Blogging Wizard</a>, 2026)
Businesses ranking in positions 4 to 10 average fewer than 200 images. Photo count correlates with ranking position.</p>
<p><strong>32. Profiles with 15 or more photos per location see stronger engagement across all actions.</strong>
(Source: Birdeye, 2025)
15 photos is the minimum threshold for meaningful engagement improvement.</p>
